  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>You are sick. Your head is a pressure vessel, your sinuses have declared martial law, and you are standing in a pharmacy aisle at 9 p.m. reading the back of a DayQuil box like it contains useful information. You reach for the Sudafed PE — or maybe the Theraflu, or the Mucinex Sinus-Max. The box says "Nasal Decongestant." In large, confident type. In September 2023, an FDA advisory panel voted unanimously that the primary active ingredient in most of those products — oral phenylephrine — works no better than a sugar pill. The products are still on the shelf.</p>
</section>

<section id="how-it-happened" class="reveal">
  <h2>How a placebo became a $1.8 billion market</h2>
  <p>This is not a story about corporate malfeasance in the cinematic sense. It is quieter and, in some ways, more damning: a regulatory system that failed at the most ordinary possible task and kept failing for nearly two decades while Americans spent $1.8 billion annually on bottles of expensive nothing.</p>
  <p>Pseudoephedrine — the decongestant that actually works — was moved behind pharmacy counters in 2006 under the Combat Methamphetamine Epidemic Act, because it can be used to synthesize meth. The restriction did not meaningfully reduce methamphetamine use, as subsequent data would show. What it did do was hand manufacturers a problem: their flagship decongestants were now bureaucratically inconvenient. The solution was phenylephrine. It was cheap, it was already approved, and it sat comfortably on open shelves.</p>
  <p>Phenylephrine taken orally is inactivated by enzymes in the gut before it can reach the nasal passages in any clinically useful concentration. University of Florida pharmacists Leslie Hendeles and Randy Hatton had been documenting this since the mid-2000s, filing citizen petitions and testifying before advisory committees. In 2007, an FDA panel heard the evidence and concluded only that more studies were needed. More studies arrived. They showed the same thing. The product stayed on the shelf.</p>
  <p>It took until September 2023 for the FDA's Nonprescription Drug Advisory Committee to vote — unanimously — that oral phenylephrine is not "Generally Recognized as Safe and Effective." In November 2024, the agency formally proposed removing it from the OTC monograph. A final order is expected sometime in 2026. As of today, Sudafed PE, NyQuil Severe, and roughly 250 other products containing oral phenylephrine as a decongestant are still being sold. CVS voluntarily pulled them. Most pharmacies did not.</p>
  <p>The 2021 meta-analysis in the <em>Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology: In Practice</em>, funded independently by the University of Florida without pharmaceutical industry support, proved influential in the FDA's re-evaluation and found that oral phenylephrine was not significantly more effective than placebo for relieving nasal congestion. This was not a surprise to anyone who had been reading the literature. It was a surprise, apparently, to the system designed to prevent this from happening.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"If you have a stuffy nose and you take this medicine, you will still have a stuffy nose."</p></aside>

<section id="important-distinction" class="reveal">
  <h2>One distinction that actually matters</h2>
  <p>Before proceeding: the ineffectiveness finding applies specifically to oral phenylephrine at approved OTC doses. Nasal spray decongestants — oxymetazoline (Afrin), and phenylephrine in spray form — are effective for short-term use, up to three days. Pseudoephedrine, still available behind the pharmacy counter with ID, has consistent evidence of efficacy. The story is not "all decongestants are useless." The story is that the one formulation that replaced the effective product on open shelves turned out to be the one that doesn't work.</p>
</section>

<div class="data-callout reveal"><p><strong>What the FDA actually said</strong></p><p>The Nonprescription Drug Advisory Committee voted unanimously in September 2023 that oral phenylephrine is not Generally Recognized as Safe and Effective (GRASE) as a nasal decongestant. The FDA's own pre-meeting analysis reached the same conclusion: ineffective at standard doses and at higher doses. No safety concerns were identified. The FDA formally proposed removal in November 2024; a final order is expected in 2026. Until then, products remain legally marketable.</p></div>

<section id="what-works-for-cough" class="reveal">
  <h2>The thing beating cough syrup is in your kitchen</h2>
  <p>Dextromethorphan — the "DM" in NyQuil, Robitussin DM, and dozens of other products — is the best-selling cough suppressant in America. The evidence for it is, to be charitable, thin. A 2018 Cochrane review—still the most recent comprehensive analysis despite newer small studies—examined honey for acute cough and found it likely more effective than no treatment, more effective than placebo, and possibly superior to dextromethorphan for reducing cough frequency and severity. The comparison drug lost to a pantry staple.</p>
  <p>Honey works through a combination of physical throat-coating, mild antimicrobial properties, and direct soothing of irritated tissue — the evidence is cleaner than what supports the product in the branded bottle next to it on the shelf. One caveat that matters: honey is not safe for children under one year old due to the risk of infant botulism.</p>
  <p>Guaifenesin — the expectorant in Mucinex and countless multi-symptom products — has a similar problem. The claim is that it thins mucus, making it easier to clear. The clinical trial data supporting meaningful benefit at OTC doses is weak. It is not harmful. It is mostly expensive water.</p>
</section>

<section id="zinc-complicated" class="reveal">
  <h2>Zinc: the honest version</h2>
  <p>Zinc is where the "natural remedies vs. pharma" framing — the lazy version of this story — falls apart. Zinc is not a folk remedy being rehabilitated by wellness culture. It has real Cochrane-level evidence. It also has real limitations, and anyone overselling it is doing the same thing the DayQuil marketers do.</p>
  <p>The 2024 Cochrane review on zinc for the common cold found low-certainty evidence that zinc taken for treatment may reduce cold duration by approximately two days. Low-certainty matters here: the trials are heterogeneous, formulations vary, effect sizes are inconsistent. Timing is everything — zinc appears to need to be started within 24 hours of symptom onset. Miss that window and the data largely evaporates. Side effects are real: nausea and a persistent metallic taste are common. Nasal zinc products have been associated with anosmia — loss of smell — serious enough that the FDA issued a safety warning about zinc-containing nasal sprays in 2009.</p>
  <p>Two fewer days of misery is not nothing. But zinc is not a proven cold cure. It is a modestly promising intervention with a narrow therapeutic window, real side effects, and evidence the scientific community grades as low-certainty. Take that for what it is.</p>
</section>

<section id="sleep-data" class="reveal">
  <h2>The intervention nobody is selling you</h2>
  <p>In 2009, researchers at Carnegie Mellon University published a study in the <em>Archives of Internal Medicine</em> that deserves more cultural traction than it gets. They recruited 153 healthy volunteers, monitored their sleep habits for two weeks with phone interviews, then deliberately exposed them to a rhinovirus — the most common cause of the common cold — via nasal drops. They then quarantined participants for five days and measured clinical illness.</p>
  <p>Participants who averaged fewer than seven hours of sleep per night were 2.94 times more likely to develop a clinical cold than those who slept eight hours or more. Nearly three times. This was a controlled rhinovirus exposure study. Not a survey. Not self-reported outcomes. They gave people a cold on purpose and watched what happened.</p>
  <p>Sleep deprivation suppresses natural killer cell activity and impairs cytokine production. The intervention with perhaps the strongest data for cold prevention is also the one with the lowest profit margin: it is free, it requires no packaging, and it cannot be branded.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The intervention with the strongest prevention data is free, requires no packaging, and cannot be branded."</p></aside>

<section id="vitamin-c-elderberry" class="reveal">
  <h2>Vitamin C and elderberry: calibrate expectations accordingly</h2>
  <p>Vitamin C, if taken regularly — not therapeutically after you are already symptomatic — may modestly reduce cold duration. The 2013 Cochrane review found an 8% reduction in adults and 14% in children with daily supplementation of 0.2g or more. That is roughly half a day less sick. It does not prevent colds in the general population. Starting vitamin C after symptoms appear has not shown consistent benefit. The evidence for megadosing is not there. Take regular supplementation for what it is: a small, consistent effect, not a remedy.</p>
  <p>Elderberry has preliminary positive signals from small studies, including some evidence of shortened symptom duration in upper respiratory infections, but these are often industry-funded by supplement makers; the evidence is not sufficient to make a firm recommendation, and larger independent trials are needed to rule out bias. "Emerging" is the accurate word; "proven" is not.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-simple-stuff" class="reveal">
  <h2>Salt water, fluids, time</h2>
  <p>Salt water gargling has evidence for sore throat relief. Hydration — warm or cold liquids — soothes irritated tissue and keeps the airways clear. A humidifier in a dry winter bedroom reduces airway irritation. Ibuprofen and acetaminophen have solid evidence for symptomatic sore throat relief; they are among the most evidence-supported interventions in this entire category. None of them generate $1.8 billion in annual revenue.</p>
  <p>Antibiotics are ineffective against viruses. Roughly 30% of antibiotic prescriptions in outpatient settings are for conditions — upper respiratory infections, nearly all viral — where they accomplish nothing except advancing resistance. If a physician prescribes antibiotics for a common cold without first establishing bacterial infection, that is worth questioning directly.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-actual-conclusion" class="reveal">
  <h2>What you are buying when you buy that box</h2>
  <p>What the evidence actually supports: sleep, with a 2.94x effect size in controlled exposure that no supplement in this category can match. Honey for cough. Salt water. Fluids. Ibuprofen or acetaminophen for sore throat pain. Zinc lozenges if you catch the onset within 24 hours and can tolerate the side effects. Nasal spray decongestants — oxymetazoline, or phenylephrine in spray form — for congestion, short-term. Pseudoephedrine from behind the pharmacy counter if you want an oral option that actually reaches your nose.</p>
  <p>What the FDA's own panel concluded does not work: the primary decongestant in most of the products on the open shelf. The evidence of this was building in 2007. University of Florida pharmacists filed petitions. Studies arrived. The conclusion was the same each time. The products stayed on the shelves for another sixteen years. This is not a conspiracy — it is how regulatory inertia works when a product is cheap, ubiquitous, and not dangerous enough to force emergency action. The harm is diffuse: a few dollars per box, multiplied by 242 million units sold in a single year, collected from people who were already miserable and just wanted to breathe.</p>
  <p>The most effective cold interventions are the least profitable ones. That symmetry is not sinister. It is just how markets work. What's remarkable is how little it took to obscure it — some confident packaging, a $12 price point, and a regulatory system that moved at the speed of a committee.</p>
</section>

